---
description: Defines the official folder and file organization for the LexMastery Flutter application.

alwaysApply: true
---

# Folder Structure

The LexMastery Flutter application follows a Feature-First Modular Clean Architecture.

Every file must have a single, obvious home.

Never create new top-level folders without explicit approval.

---

# Root Structure

lib/

app/

core/

shared/

features/

main.dart

No additional top-level folders are allowed.

---

# app/

The app folder contains application bootstrapping.

Responsible for:

Application initialization

App widget

Router configuration

Global providers

Dependency registration

Theme registration

Environment selection

App lifecycle

Allowed folders:

app/

config/

router/

theme/

bootstrap/

startup/

Do not place business logic here.

---

# core/

Core contains infrastructure used across the application.

Allowed folders:

analytics/

constants/

environment/

errors/

extensions/

logging/

network/

services/

storage/

utils/

exceptions/

mixins/

Core must never contain business logic.

---

# shared/

Shared contains reusable UI and design system resources.

Allowed folders:

components/

tokens/

typography/

icons/

animations/

layouts/

validators/

widgets/

extensions/

A component belongs in Shared only if it is reused by three or more features.

Otherwise, keep it inside the owning feature.

---

# features/

Every business capability belongs inside features/.

Each feature is independent.

Example:

features/

authentication/

onboarding/

dashboard/

courses/

learning/

flashcards/

quizzes/

mock_exams/

ai_tutor/

ai_instructor/

diagnostics/

comparative_law/

analytics/

notifications/

profile/

settings/

accessibility/

---

# Feature Structure

Each feature must follow the same internal structure.

feature/

presentation/

domain/

data/

routes/

assets/

tests/

---

# Presentation

Responsible for UI.

presentation/

screens/

widgets/

controllers/

providers/

state/

dialogs/

bottom_sheets/

forms/

animations/

Presentation must never contain business logic.

---

# Domain

Responsible for business rules.

domain/

entities/

repositories/

usecases/

value_objects/

services/

policies/

Domain must remain pure Dart.

Never import Flutter.

---

# Data

Responsible for persistence.

data/

datasources/

repositories/

dto/

mappers/

models/

cache/

remote/

local/

Never expose DTOs outside Data.

---

# Routes

Each feature owns its routes.

routes/

feature_routes.dart

Global routing is composed from feature routes.

---

# Assets

Feature-specific assets remain inside the feature.

Examples:

Empty illustrations

Lottie files

Icons

Do not duplicate assets already available globally.

---

# Tests

Every feature owns its own tests.

tests/

unit/

widget/

golden/

integration/

Keep tests close to the feature.

---

# Naming Rules

Folders:

snake_case

Examples:

study_plan

ai_tutor

mock_exams

Files:

snake_case.dart

Examples:

login_screen.dart

dashboard_controller.dart

course_repository.dart

Classes:

PascalCase

Examples:

LoginScreen

DashboardController

CourseRepository

Variables:

camelCase

Methods:

camelCase

Constants:

lowerCamelCase unless compile-time constants require Dart's `lowerCamelCase` convention.

---

# One Class Per File

Every public class belongs in its own file.

Avoid multiple unrelated classes in one file.

---

# Widget Rules

Do not place reusable widgets inside screens/.

Place them in:

presentation/widgets/

Large screens should be composed from many smaller widgets.

---

# Controller Rules

Controllers live only in:

presentation/controllers/

Never place controllers inside widgets.

---

# State Rules

State classes belong in:

presentation/state/

Keep state immutable.

---

# Provider Rules

Riverpod providers belong in:

presentation/providers/

Avoid placing providers in arbitrary folders.

---

# Repository Rules

Repository interfaces:

domain/repositories/

Repository implementations:

data/repositories/

Never combine both.

---

# Use Case Rules

Every business action becomes one Use Case.

Examples:

login_user.dart

submit_assessment.dart

generate_study_plan.dart

Never place multiple unrelated use cases in one file.

---

# DTO Rules

DTOs belong only in:

data/dto/

Never expose DTOs to the UI.

---

# Mapper Rules

Every DTO should have a mapper.

Location:

data/mappers/

Mapping logic should never appear inside controllers.

---

# Network Rules

Networking belongs only in:

core/network/

Features never configure Dio directly.

---

# Storage Rules

Hive

Secure Storage

Shared Preferences

must all be abstracted through:

core/storage/

---

# Environment Rules

Environment configuration belongs in:

core/environment/

Never hardcode URLs.

Never hardcode API keys.

---

# Shared Components

Examples:

PrimaryButton

SecondaryButton

AppCard

ProgressRing

Avatar

SearchBar

LegalReferenceCard

Only create shared components after proving reuse.

---

# Documentation

Every feature should contain a README.md explaining:

Purpose

Architecture

Dependencies

API endpoints

Known limitations

Future improvements

---

# Cursor Instructions

Before creating a file:

Identify its feature.

Identify its layer.

Verify ownership.

Verify naming.

Verify dependencies.

Only then generate the file.

Never invent new folder structures.

Always follow this hierarchy.